<p>A <b>binary number</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Num=
ber" title=3D"Number">number</a> expressed in the <b>base-2 numeral system<=
/b> or <b>binary numeral system</b>, a method for representing <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number" title=3D"Number">numbers</a> that uses=
 only two symbols for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_=
number" title=3D"Natural number">natural numbers</a>: typically <span class=
=3D"nounderlines" style=3D"border: 1px solid var(--border-color-muted,#ddd)=
; color: var(--color-base,#202122); background-color: var( --background-col=
or-neutral-subtle, #fdfdfd); padding: 1px 1px;">0</span> (<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Zero">zero</a>=
) and <span class=3D"nounderlines" style=3D"border: 1px solid var(--border-=
color-muted,#ddd); color: var(--color-base,#202122); background-color: var(=
 --background-color-neutral-subtle, #fdfdfd); padding: 1px 1px;">1</span> (=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"One">one</a>). A <i>binary number</i>  may also refer to a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D"Rational number">rat=
ional number</a> that has a finite representation in the binary numeral sys=
tem, that is, the quotient of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
nteger" title=3D"Integer">integer</a> by a power of two.
</p><p>The base-2 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numeral_system" =
title=3D"Numeral system">numeral system</a> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Positional_notation" title=3D"Positional notation">positiona=
l notation</a> with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" title=
=3D"Radix">radix</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2" title=
=3D"2">2</a>. Each digit is referred to as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bit</a>, or binary digit. Because of its stra=
ightforward implementation in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digi=
tal_electronic_circuit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Digital electronic c=
ircuit">digital electronic circuitry</a> using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Logic_gate" title=3D"Logic gate">logic gates</a>, the binary s=
ystem is used by almost all modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Computer" title=3D"Computer">computers and computer-based devices</a>, as =
a preferred system of use, over various other human techniques of communica=
tion, because of the simplicity of the language and the noise immunity in p=
hysical implementation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-1"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
