<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The modern  binary number system was studied in Europe in the 16th and 1=
7th centuries by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Harriot" t=
itle=3D"Thomas Harriot">Thomas Harriot</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Leibniz" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gottfried L=
eibniz">Gottfried Leibniz</a>. However, systems related to binary numbers h=
ave appeared earlier in multiple cultures including ancient Egypt, China, E=
urope and India.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Egypt">Egypt</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Egypt"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egyptian_mathematics" title=
=3D"Ancient Egyptian mathematics">Ancient Egyptian mathematics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Eye_of_Ra_(fractions).svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/8/89/Eye_of_Ra_%28fractions%29.svg/250px-Eye_of_Ra_%28frac=
tions%29.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"141" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1279" data-file-height=3D"723"></a><fig=
caption>Arithmetic values thought to have been represented by parts of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_of_Horus" title=3D"Eye of Horu=
s">Eye of Horus</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The scribes of ancient Egypt used two different systems for their fracti=
ons, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_fraction" title=3D"E=
gyptian fraction">Egyptian fractions</a> (not related to the binary number =
system) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_of_Horus" title=3D=
"Eye of Horus">Horus-Eye</a> fractions (so called because some historians o=
f mathematics believed that the symbols used for this system could be arran=
ged to form the eye of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horus" titl=
e=3D"Horus">Horus</a>, although this has been disputed).<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_num=
ber#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Horus-Eye fractions are a binary numbering syst=
em for fractional quantities of grain, liquids, or other measures, in which=
 a fraction of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hekat" title=3D"H=
ekat">hekat</a> is expressed as a sum of the binary fractions 1/2, 1/4, 1/8=
, 1/16, 1/32, and 1/64. Early forms of this system can be found in document=
s from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_Dynasty_of_Egypt"=
 title=3D"Fifth Dynasty of Egypt">Fifth Dynasty of Egypt</a>, approximately=
 2400 BC, and its fully developed hieroglyphic form dates to the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nineteenth_Dynasty_of_Egypt" title=3D"Ninete=
enth Dynasty of Egypt">Nineteenth Dynasty of Egypt</a>, approximately 1200 =
BC.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The method used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient=
_Egyptian_multiplication" title=3D"Ancient Egyptian multiplication">ancient=
 Egyptian multiplication</a> is also closely related to binary numbers. In =
this method, multiplying one number by a second is performed by a sequence =
of steps in which a value (initially the first of the two numbers) is eithe=
r doubled or has the first number added back into it; the order in which th=
ese steps are to be performed is given by the binary representation of the =
second number. This method can be seen in use, for instance, in the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhind_Mathematical_Papyrus" title=3D"Rhin=
d Mathematical Papyrus">Rhind Mathematical Papyrus</a>, which dates to arou=
nd 1650 BC.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"China">China</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: China"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bagua-name-earlier.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4=
/4d/Bagua-name-earlier.svg/250px-Bagua-name-earlier.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"547" data-file-height=3D"547"></a><figcaption>Daoist Bagua</figcaption>=
</figure>
<p>The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Ching" title=3D"I Chin=
g">I Ching</a></i> dates from the 9th century BC in China.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-HackerMoore2002_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-HackerMoore2002-5"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The binary =
notation in the <i>I Ching</i> is used to interpret its <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternary_numeral_system" title=3D"Quaternary numera=
l system">quaternary</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Ching_d=
ivination" title=3D"I Ching divination">divination</a> technique.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-redmond-hon_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-redmond-hon-6"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It is based on taoistic duality of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Yin_and_yang" title=3D"Yin and yang">yin and yang</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-scientific_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-scientific-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba_gua" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ba gua">Eigh=
t trigrams (Bagua)</a> and a set of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Hexagram_(I_Ching)" title=3D"Hexagram (I Ching)">64 hexagrams ("sixty-fou=
r" gua)</a>, analogous to the three-bit and six-bit binary numerals, were i=
n use at least as early as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zho=
u_dynasty" title=3D"Zhou dynasty">Zhou dynasty</a> of ancient China.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-HackerMoore2002_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-HackerMoore2002-5"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Song_dynasty" title=3D"=
Song dynasty">Song dynasty</a> scholar <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Shao_Yong" title=3D"Shao Yong">Shao Yong</a> (1011=E2=80=931077) rearr=
anged the hexagrams in a format that resembles modern binary numbers, altho=
ugh he did not intend his arrangement to be used mathematically.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-redmond-hon_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-redmond-hon-6"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Viewing the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_significant_bit" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Least significant bit">least significant bit</a> on top =
of single hexagrams in Shao Yong's square<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Marshall_8-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#=
cite_note-Marshall-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
and reading along rows either from bottom right to top left with solid line=
s as 0 and broken lines as 1 or from top left to bottom right with solid li=
nes as 1 and broken lines as 0 hexagrams can be interpreted as sequence fro=
m 0 to 63.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Shao_Yong=E2=80=99s_=E2=80=9DXiantian_Tu'=E2=80=98_9-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number=
#cite_note-Shao_Yong%E2%80%99s_%E2%80%9DXiantian_Tu'%E2%80%98-9"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Classical_antiquity">Classi=
cal antiquity</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DBinary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: =
Classical antiquity"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Etruscan_civilization" title=3D=
"Etruscan civilization">Etruscans</a> divided the outer edge of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haruspex" title=3D"Haruspex">divination liver=
s</a> into sixteen parts, each inscribed with the name of a divinity and it=
s region of the sky. Each liver region produced a binary reading which was =
combined into a final binary for divination.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_=
note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Divination at Ancient Greek <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Dodona" title=3D"Dodona">Dodona</a> oracle worked by drawing from separate=
 jars, questions tablets and "yes" and "no" pellets. The result was then co=
mbined to make a final prophecy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-11"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"India">India</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: India"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Indian scholar <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pingala" tit=
le=3D"Pingala">Pingala</a> (c. 2nd century BC) developed a binary system fo=
r describing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prosody_(poetry)" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prosody (poetry)">prosody</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_=
number#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-13"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> He described meters in the form of short and long syllables (the lat=
ter equal in length to two short syllables).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_=
note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> They were known as <i>laghu</i> (light) and <i>guru</i=
> (heavy) syllables.
</p><p>Pingala's Hindu classic titled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Chanda%E1%B8%A5%C5%9B%C4%81stra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chanda=
=E1=B8=A5=C5=9B=C4=81stra">Chanda=E1=B8=A5=C5=9B=C4=81stra</a> (8.23) descr=
ibes the formation of a matrix in order to give a unique value to each mete=
r. "Chanda=E1=B8=A5=C5=9B=C4=81stra" literally translates to <i>science of =
meters</i> in Sanskrit. The binary representations in Pingala's system incr=
eases towards the right, and not to the left like in the binary numbers of =
the modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positional_notation" ti=
tle=3D"Positional notation">positional notation</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number=
#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> In Pingala's system, the numbers start from numb=
er one, and not zero. Four short syllables "0000" is the first pattern and =
corresponds to the value one. The numerical value is obtained by adding one=
 to the sum of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Place_value" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Place value">place values</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_nu=
mber#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Africa">Africa</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Africa"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/If%C3%A1" title=3D"If=C3=A1=
">If=C3=A1</a> is an African divination system<i>.</i> Similar to the <i>I =
Ching</i>, but has up to 256 binary signs,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note=
-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> unlike the <i>I Ching</i> which has 64. The If=C3=A1 origi=
nated in 15th century West Africa among <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Yoruba_people" title=3D"Yoruba people">Yoruba people</a>. In 2008, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNESCO" title=3D"UNESCO">UNESCO</a> =
added If=C3=A1 to its list of the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Masterpieces_of_the_Oral_and_Intangible_Heritage_of_Humanity" title=3D"Mas=
terpieces of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity">Masterpieces of =
the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTELandry2019154_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-FOOTNOTELandry2019154-18"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_cultures">Other cultu=
res</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_n=
umber&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Other cultu=
res"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>The residents of the island of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mangareva" title=3D"Mangareva">Mangareva</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/French_Polynesia" title=3D"French Polynesia">French Polynesia=
</a> were using a hybrid binary-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De=
cimal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> system before 1450.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_nu=
mber#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sli=
t_drum" title=3D"Slit drum">Slit drums</a> with binary tones are used to en=
code messages across Africa and Asia.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-scientific_7-1" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#ci=
te_note-scientific-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Sets of binary combinations similar to the <i>I Ching</i> have also been us=
ed in traditional African divination systems, such as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/If%C3%A1" title=3D"If=C3=A1">If=C3=A1</a> among others,=
 as well as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ages" title=
=3D"Middle Ages">medieval</a> Western <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Geomancy" title=3D"Geomancy">geomancy</a>. The majority of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Aboriginal_languages" title=3D"Aust=
ralian Aboriginal languages">Indigenous Australian languages</a> use a base=
-2 system.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Western_predecessors_to_Lei=
bniz">Western predecessors to Leibniz</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" =
title=3D"Edit section: Western predecessors to Leibniz"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the late 13th century <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramon_=
Llull" title=3D"Ramon Llull">Ramon Llull</a> had the ambition to account fo=
r all wisdom in every branch of human knowledge of the time. For that purpo=
se he developed a general method or "Ars generalis" based on binary combina=
tions of a number of simple basic principles or categories, for which he ha=
s been considered a predecessor of computing science and artificial intelli=
gence.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1605, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Bacon" tit=
le=3D"Francis Bacon">Francis Bacon</a> discussed a system whereby letters o=
f the alphabet could be reduced to sequences of binary digits, which could =
then be encoded as scarcely visible variations in the font in any random te=
xt.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bacon1605_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-Bacon1605-23"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Importantly for the general theory of binary encoding, he added that this =
method could be used with any objects at all: "provided those objects be ca=
pable of a twofold difference only; as by Bells, by Trumpets, by Lights and=
 Torches, by the report of Muskets, and any instruments of like nature".<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Bacon1605_23-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-Bacon1605-23"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (See <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacon%27s_cipher" title=3D"Bacon's =
cipher">Bacon's cipher</a>.)
</p><p>In 1617, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Napier" title=
=3D"John Napier">John Napier</a> described a system he called <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Location_arithmetic" title=3D"Location arithmet=
ic">location arithmetic</a> for doing binary calculations using a non-posit=
ional representation by letters.
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Harriot" title=3D"Thomas Ha=
rriot">Thomas Harriot</a> investigated several positional numbering systems=
, including binary, but did not publish his results; they were found later =
among his papers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Possibly the first publication of the system in Europe was by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Caramuel_y_Lobkowitz" title=3D"Juan Caramu=
el y Lobkowitz">Juan Caramuel y Lobkowitz</a>, in 1700.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_num=
ber#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Leibniz">Leibniz</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Leibniz"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz,_Bernhard_Christoph=
_Francke.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wiki=
media.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz%2C_Bernhar=
d_Christoph_Francke.jpg/250px-Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz%2C_Bernhard_Christo=
ph_Francke.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"235" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4486" data-file-height=3D"5538"></a><figc=
aption>Gottfried Leibniz</figcaption></figure>
<p>Leibniz wrote in excess of a hundred manuscripts on binary, most of them=
 remaining unpublished.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-:0-26"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Before his first dedicated work in 1679, numerous manuscripts feature=
 early attempts to explore binary concepts, including tables of numbers and=
 basic calculations, often scribbled in the margins of works unrelated to m=
athematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_26-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-:0-26"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>His first known work on binary, <i>=E2=80=9COn the Binary Progressio=
n"</i>, in 1679, Leibniz introduced conversion between decimal and binary, =
along with algorithms for performing basic arithmetic operations such as ad=
dition, subtraction, multiplication, and division using binary numbers. He =
also developed a form of binary algebra to calculate the square of a six-di=
git number and to extract square roots.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_26-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_=
note-:0-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>His most well known work appears in his article <i>Explication de l'=
Arithm=C3=A9tique Binaire</i> (published in 1703).
The full title of Leibniz's article is translated into English as the <i>"E=
xplanation of Binary Arithmetic, which uses only the characters 1 and 0, wi=
th some remarks on its usefulness, and on the light it throws on the ancien=
t Chinese figures of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fu_Xi" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fu Xi">Fu Xi</a>"</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-lnz_27-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numb=
er#cite_note-lnz-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Leibniz's system uses 0 and 1, like the mo=
dern binary numeral system. An example of Leibniz's binary numeral system i=
s as follows:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-lnz_27-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-lnz-27"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd>0 0 0 1 &nbsp; numerical value 2<sup>0</sup></dd>
<dd>0 0 1 0 &nbsp; numerical value 2<sup>1</sup></dd>
<dd>0 1 0 0 &nbsp; numerical value 2<sup>2</sup></dd>
<dd>1 0 0 0 &nbsp; numerical value 2<sup>3</sup></dd></dl>
<p>While corresponding with the Jesuit priest <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Joachim_Bouvet" title=3D"Joachim Bouvet">Joachim Bouvet</a> in =
1700, who had made himself an expert on the <i>I Ching</i> while a missiona=
ry in China, Leibniz explained his binary notation, and Bouvet demonstrated=
 in his 1701 letters that the <i>I Ching</i> was an independent, parallel i=
nvention of binary notation.
Leibniz &amp; Bouvet concluded that this mapping was evidence of major Chin=
ese accomplishments in the sort of philosophical <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> he admire=
d.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Of this parallel invent=
ion, Leibniz wrote in his "Explanation Of Binary Arithmetic" that "this res=
titution of their meaning, after such a great interval of time, will seem a=
ll the more curious."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The relation was a central idea to his universal concept of a langua=
ge or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristica_universalis"=
 title=3D"Characteristica universalis">characteristica universalis</a>, a p=
opular idea that would be followed closely by his successors such as <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottlob_Frege" title=3D"Gottlob Frege">G=
ottlob Frege</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Boole"=
 title=3D"George Boole">George Boole</a> in forming <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_Calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pr=
opositional Calculus">modern symbolic logic</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cit=
e_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
Leibniz was first introduced to the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/I_Ching" title=3D"I Ching">I Ching</a></i> through his contact with th=
e French Jesuit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joachim_Bouvet" ti=
tle=3D"Joachim Bouvet">Joachim Bouvet</a>, who visited China in 1685 as a m=
issionary. Leibniz saw the <i>I Ching</i> hexagrams as an affirmation of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universality_(philosophy)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Universality (philosophy)">universality</a> of hi=
s own religious beliefs as a Christian.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-smith_31-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite=
_note-smith-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Binary numerals were central to Leibniz's theol=
ogy. He believed that binary numbers were symbolic of the Christian idea of=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creatio_ex_nihilo" title=3D"Cr=
eatio ex nihilo">creatio ex nihilo</a></i> or creation out of nothing.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-lniz_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-lniz-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>[A concept that] is not easy to impa=
rt to the pagans, is the creation <i>ex nihilo</i> through God's almighty p=
ower. Now one can say that nothing in the world can better present and demo=
nstrate this power than the origin of numbers, as it is presented here thro=
ugh the simple and unadorned presentation of One and Zero or Nothing.</p></=
blockquote><div class=3D"templatequotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline; pa=
dding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8ALeibniz's letter to the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolph_Augustus,_Duke_of_Brunswick-L%C3%BCnebu=
rg" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rudolph Augustus, Duke of Brunswick-L=C3=
=BCneburg">Duke of Brunswick</a> attached with the <i>I Ching</i> hexagrams=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-smith_31-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-smith-31"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><span style=
=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></span></p></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Later_developments">Later d=
evelopments</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Binary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: La=
ter developments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:George_Boole_color.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/c/ce/George_Boole_color.jpg/250px-George_Boole_color.jpg" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"333" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"600" data-file-height=3D"800"></a><figcaption>George Boole<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>In 1854, British mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
George_Boole" title=3D"George Boole">George Boole</a> published a landmark =
paper detailing an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=
=3D"Algebra">algebraic</a> system of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">logic</a> that would become known as <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(logic)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Boolean algebra (logic)">Boolean algebra</a>. His logical calculu=
s was to become instrumental in the design of digital electronic circuitry.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1937, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Shannon" ti=
tle=3D"Claude Shannon">Claude Shannon</a> produced his master's thesis at <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"MIT">MIT</a> that implemented Boolean algebra and binary arithmetic using =
electronic relays and switches for the first time in history. Entitled <i><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Symbolic_Analysis_of_Relay_and_Sw=
itching_Circuits" title=3D"A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circu=
its">A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits</a></i>, Shannon's=
 thesis essentially founded practical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Digital_circuit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Digital circuit">digita=
l circuit</a> design.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In November 1937, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_St=
ibitz" title=3D"George Stibitz">George Stibitz</a>, then working at <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bell_Labs" title=3D"Bell Labs">Bell Labs<=
/a>, completed a relay-based computer he dubbed the "Model K" (for "<b>K</b=
>itchen", where he had assembled it), which calculated using binary additio=
n.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Bell Labs authorized a =
full research program in late 1938 with Stibitz at the helm. Their Complex =
Number Computer, completed 8 January 1940, was able to calculate <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Complex numbers">complex numbers</a>. In a demonstration to the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Mathematical_Society" title=3D"A=
merican Mathematical Society">American Mathematical Society</a> conference =
at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dartmouth_College" title=3D"Dar=
tmouth College">Dartmouth College</a> on 11 September 1940, Stibitz was abl=
e to send the Complex Number Calculator remote commands over telephone line=
s by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teleprinter" title=3D"Telep=
rinter">teletype</a>. It was the first computing machine ever used remotely=
 over a phone line. Some participants of the conference who witnessed the d=
emonstration were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann=
" title=3D"John von Neumann">John von Neumann</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/John_Mauchly" title=3D"John Mauchly">John Mauchly</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norbert_Wiener" title=3D"Norbert W=
iener">Norbert Wiener</a>, who wrote about it in his memoirs.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bina=
ry_number#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-37"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z1_(computer)" title=3D=
"Z1 (computer)">Z1 computer</a>, which was designed and built by <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Konrad_Zuse" title=3D"Konrad Zuse">Konrad Zu=
se</a> between 1935 and 1938, used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Boolean_logic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boolean logic">Boolean logic=
</a> and binary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_ari=
thmetic" title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floating-point numbers</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-zuse_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-zuse-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Representation">Representat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_n=
umber&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Representa=
tion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>Any number can be represented by a sequence of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bit" title=3D"Bit">bits</a> (binary digits), which in turn =
may be represented by any mechanism capable of being in two mutually exclus=
ive states. Any of the following rows of symbols can be interpreted as the =
binary numeric value of 667:
</p>
