<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Subtraction">Subtraction</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Subtraction"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signed_number=
_representations" title=3D"Signed number representations">signed number rep=
resentations</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two%27s_compl=
ement" title=3D"Two's complement">two's complement</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Subtracti=
on">Subtraction</a> works in much the same way:
</p>
<dl><dd>0 =E2=88=92 0 =E2=86=92 0</dd>
<dd>0 =E2=88=92 1 =E2=86=92 1, borrow 1</dd>
<dd>1 =E2=88=92 0 =E2=86=92 1</dd>
<dd>1 =E2=88=92 1 =E2=86=92 0</dd></dl>
<p>Subtracting a "1" digit from a "0" digit produces the digit "1", while 1=
 will have to be subtracted from the next column. This is known as <i>borro=
wing</i>. The principle is the same as for carrying. When the result of a s=
ubtraction is less than 0, the least possible value of a digit, the procedu=
re is to "borrow" the deficit divided by the radix (that is, 10/10) from th=
e left, subtracting it from the next positional value.
</p>
<pre>    *   * * *   (starred columns are borrowed from)
  1 1 0 1 1 1 0
=E2=88=92     1 0 1 1 1
----------------
=3D 1 0 1 0 1 1 1
</pre>
<pre>  *             (starred columns are borrowed from)
  1 0 1 1 1 1 1
=E2=80=93   1 0 1 0 1 1
----------------
=3D 0 1 1 0 1 0 0
</pre>
<p>Subtracting a positive number is equivalent to <i>adding</i> a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_number" title=3D"Negative number=
">negative number</a> of equal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abs=
olute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">absolute value</a>. Computers use <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signed_number_representations" title=
=3D"Signed number representations">signed number representations</a> to han=
dle negative numbers=E2=80=94most commonly the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Two%27s_complement" title=3D"Two's complement">two's complemen=
t</a> notation. Such representations eliminate the need for a separate "sub=
tract" operation. Using two's complement notation, subtraction can be summa=
rized by the following formula:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml">A =E2=88=92 B =3D A + not B + 1</span></dd>=
</dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Multiplication">Multiplicat=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_n=
umber&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Multiplica=
tion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multip=
lication">Multiplication</a> in binary is similar to its decimal counterpar=
t. Two numbers <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:T=
emplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">A</var> and <link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r100322724=
9"><var class=3D"var-serif">B</var> can be multiplied by partial products: =
for each digit in <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-dat=
a:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">B</var>, the product=
 of that digit in <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-dat=
a:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">A</var> is calculate=
d and written on a new line, shifted leftward so that its rightmost digit l=
ines up with the digit in <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">B</var> th=
at was used. The sum of all these partial products gives the final result.
</p><p>Since there are only two digits in binary, there are only two possib=
le outcomes of each partial multiplication:
</p>
<ul><li>If the digit in <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"=
mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">B</var> is 0, =
the partial product is also 0</li>
<li>If the digit in <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-d=
ata:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">B</var> is 1, the =
partial product is equal to <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">A</var></l=
i></ul>
<p>For example, the binary numbers 1011 and 1010 are multiplied as follows:
</p>
<pre>           1 0 1 1   (<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">A</var>)
         =C3=97 1 0 1 0   (<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">B</var>)
         ---------
           0 0 0 0   =E2=86=90 to the rightmost 'zero' in <link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var =
class=3D"var-serif">B</var>
   +     1 0 1 1     =E2=86=90 to the next 'one' in <link rel=3D"mw-dedupli=
cated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=
=3D"var-serif">B</var>
   +   0 0 0 0
   + 1 0 1 1
   ---------------
   =3D 1 1 0 1 1 1 0
</pre>
<p>Binary numbers can also be multiplied with bits after a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binar=
y point">binary point</a>:
</p>
<pre>               1 0 1 . 1 0 1     <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-s=
tyle" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">=
A</var> (5.625 in decimal)
             =C3=97 1 1 0 . 0 1       <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-s=
tyle" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">=
B</var> (6.25 in decimal)
             -------------------
                   1 . 0 1 1 0 1   =E2=86=90 to a 'one' in <link rel=3D"mw-=
deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var=
 class=3D"var-serif">B</var>
     +           0 0 . 0 0 0 0     =E2=86=90 to a 'zero' in <link rel=3D"mw=
-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><va=
r class=3D"var-serif">B</var>
     +         0 0 0 . 0 0 0
     +       1 0 1 1 . 0 1
     +     1 0 1 1 0 . 1
     ---------------------------
     =3D   1 0 0 0 1 1 . 0 0 1 0 1 (35.15625 in decimal)
</pre>
<p>See also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Booth%27s_multiplicati=
on_algorithm" title=3D"Booth's multiplication algorithm">Booth's multiplica=
tion algorithm</a>.
</p>
