<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Bitwise_operations">Bitwise=
 operations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Binary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Bi=
twise operations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitwise_operation" t=
itle=3D"Bitwise operation">Bitwise operation</a></div>
<p>Though not directly related to the numerical interpretation of binary sy=
mbols, sequences of bits may be manipulated using <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Logical_connective" title=3D"Logical connective">Boolean lo=
gical operators</a>. When a string of binary symbols is manipulated in this=
 way, it is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitwise_opera=
tion" title=3D"Bitwise operation">bitwise operation</a>; the logical operat=
ors <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_conjunction" title=3D"=
Logical conjunction">AND</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logi=
cal_disjunction" title=3D"Logical disjunction">OR</a>, and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exclusive_disjunction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Exclusive disjunction">XOR</a> may be performed on corresponding bits i=
n two binary numerals provided as input. The logical <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Negation" title=3D"Negation">NOT</a> operation may be pe=
rformed on individual bits in a single binary numeral provided as input. So=
metimes, such operations may be used as arithmetic short-cuts, and may have=
 other computational benefits as well.  For example, an <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_shift" title=3D"Arithmetic shift">arithmet=
ic shift</a> left of a binary number is the equivalent of multiplication by=
 a (positive, integral) power of 2.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Conversion_to_and_from_othe=
r_numeral_systems">Conversion to and from other numeral systems</h2><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Conversion to and from ot=
her numeral systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Decimal_to_binary">Decimal =
to binary</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBi=
nary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Deci=
mal to binary"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Frame"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Decimal_to_Binary_Conversion.gif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img al=
t=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d0/Decimal_t=
o_Binary_Conversion.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"60" height=3D"218" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"60" data-file-height=3D"218"></a>=
<figcaption>Conversion of (357)<sub>10</sub> to binary notation results in =
(101100101)</figcaption></figure>
<p>To convert from a base-10 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integ=
er_(computer_science)" title=3D"Integer (computer science)">integer</a> to =
its base-2 (binary) equivalent, the number is <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Division_by_two" title=3D"Division by two">divided by two</a>. =
The remainder is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least-signifi=
cant_bit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Least-significant bit">least-signi=
ficant bit</a>. The quotient is again divided by two; its remainder becomes=
 the next least significant bit. This process repeats until a quotient of o=
ne is reached. The sequence of remainders (including the final quotient of =
one) forms the binary value, as each remainder must be either zero or one w=
hen dividing by two. For example, (357)<sub>10</sub> is expressed as (10110=
0101)<sub>2.</sub><sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Binary_to_decimal">Binary t=
o decimal</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBi=
nary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Bina=
ry to decimal"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Conversion from base-2 to base-10 simply inverts the preceding algorithm=
. The bits of the binary number are used one by one, starting with the most=
 significant (leftmost) bit. Beginning with the value 0, the prior value is=
 doubled, and the next bit is then added to produce the next value. This ca=
n be organized in a multi-column table. For example, to convert 10010101101=
<sub>2</sub> to decimal:
</p>
<table style=3D"border: 1px solid #a2a9b1; border-spacing: 3px; background-=
color: #f8f9fa; color: black; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; padding: 0.2em; li=
ne-height: 1.5em; width:22em">
