</span> in decimal).
</p><p>For very large numbers, these simple methods are inefficient because=
 they perform a large number of multiplications or divisions where one oper=
and is very large. A simple divide-and-conquer algorithm is more effective =
asymptotically: given a binary number, it is divided by 10<sup><i>k</i></su=
p>, where <i>k</i> is chosen so that the quotient roughly equals the remain=
der; then each of these pieces is converted to decimal and the two are <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concatenation" title=3D"Concatenation"=
>concatenated</a>. Given a decimal number, it can be split into two pieces =
of about the same size, each of which is converted to binary, whereupon the=
 first converted piece is multiplied by 10<sup><i>k</i></sup> and added to =
the second converted piece, where <i>k</i> is the number of decimal digits =
in the second, least-significant piece before conversion.
</p>
