<p>Binary may be converted to and from hexadecimal more easily. This is bec=
ause the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" title=3D"Radix">ra=
dix</a> of the hexadecimal system (16) is a power of the radix of the binar=
y system (2). More specifically, 16 =3D 2<sup>4</sup>, so it takes four dig=
its of binary to represent one digit of hexadecimal, as shown in the adjace=
nt table.
</p><p>To convert a hexadecimal number into its binary equivalent, simply s=
ubstitute the corresponding binary digits:
</p>
<dl><dd>3A<sub>16</sub> =3D 0011 1010<sub>2</sub></dd>
<dd>E7<sub>16</sub> =3D 1110 0111<sub>2</sub></dd></dl>
<p>To convert a binary number into its hexadecimal equivalent, divide it in=
to groups of four bits. If the number of bits is not a multiple of four, si=
mply insert extra <b>0</b> bits at the left (called <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Padding_(cryptography)#Bit_padding" title=3D"Padding (cry=
ptography)">padding</a>). For example:
</p>
<dl><dd>1010010<sub>2</sub> =3D 0101 0010 grouped with padding =3D 52<sub>1=
6</sub></dd>
<dd>11011101<sub>2</sub> =3D 1101 1101 grouped =3D DD<sub>16</sub></dd></dl=
>
<p>To convert a hexadecimal number into its decimal equivalent, multiply th=
e decimal equivalent of each hexadecimal digit by the corresponding power o=
f 16 and add the resulting values:
</p>
<dl><dd>C0E7<sub>16</sub> =3D (12 =C3=97 16<sup>3</sup>) + (0 =C3=97 16<sup=
>2</sup>) + (14 =C3=97 16<sup>1</sup>) + (7 =C3=97 16<sup>0</sup>) =3D (12 =
=C3=97 4096) + (0 =C3=97 256) + (14 =C3=97 16) + (7 =C3=97 1) =3D 49,383<su=
b>10</sub></dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Octal">Octal</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Octal"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal" title=3D"Octa=
l">Octal</a></div>
<p>Binary is also easily converted to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Octal" title=3D"Octal">octal</a> numeral system, since octal uses a=
 radix of 8, which is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_of_t=
wo" title=3D"Power of two">power of two</a> (namely, 2<sup>3</sup>, so it t=
akes exactly three binary digits to represent an octal digit). The correspo=
ndence between octal and binary numerals is the same as for the first eight=
 digits of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexadecimal" title=3D"H=
exadecimal">hexadecimal</a> in the table above. Binary 000 is equivalent to=
 the octal digit 0, binary 111 is equivalent to octal 7, and so forth.
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"text-align:center">
<tbody><tr>
<th>Octal</th>
<th>Binary
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td>0</td>
<td>000
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>001
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>010
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td>011
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>100
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>5</td>
<td>101
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>6</td>
<td>110
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>7</td>
<td>111
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Converting from octal to binary proceeds in the same fashion as it does =
for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexadecimal" title=3D"Hexadeci=
mal">hexadecimal</a>:
</p>
<dl><dd>65<sub>8</sub> =3D 110 101<sub>2</sub></dd>
<dd>17<sub>8</sub> =3D 001 111<sub>2</sub></dd></dl>
<p>And from binary to octal:
</p>
<dl><dd>101100<sub>2</sub> =3D 101 100<sub>2</sub> grouped =3D 54<sub>8</su=
b></dd>
<dd>10011<sub>2</sub> =3D 010 011<sub>2</sub> grouped with padding =3D 23<s=
ub>8</sub></dd></dl>
<p>And from octal to decimal:
</p>
<dl><dd>65<sub>8</sub> =3D (6 =C3=97 8<sup>1</sup>) + (5 =C3=97 8<sup>0</su=
p>) =3D (6 =C3=97 8) + (5 =C3=97 1) =3D 53<sub>10</sub></dd>
<dd>127<sub>8</sub> =3D (1 =C3=97 8<sup>2</sup>) + (2 =C3=97 8<sup>1</sup>)=
 + (7 =C3=97 8<sup>0</sup>) =3D (1 =C3=97 64) + (2 =C3=97 8) + (7 =C3=97 1)=
 =3D 87<sub>10</sub></dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Representing_real_numbers">=
Representing real numbers</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DBinary_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Representing real numbers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Non-integers can be represented by using negative powers, which are set =
off from the other digits by means of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Radix_point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Radix point">radix point<=
/a> (called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_point" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decimal point">decimal point</a> in the decimal s=
ystem). For example, the binary number 11.01<sub>2</sub> means:
</p>
