</p><p>The phenomenon that the binary representation of any rational is eit=
her terminating or recurring also occurs in other radix-based numeral syste=
ms. See, for instance, the explanation in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Decimal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a>. Another similarity is the e=
xistence of alternative representations for any terminating representation,=
 relying on the fact that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/0.111...=
_%3D_1_(binary)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"0.111... =3D 1 (binary)">0.=
111111...</a> is the sum of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ge=
ometric_series" title=3D"Geometric series">geometric series</a> 2<sup>=E2=
=88=921</sup> + 2<sup>=E2=88=922</sup> + 2<sup>=E2=88=923</sup> + ... which=
 is 1.
</p><p>Binary numerals that neither terminate nor recur represent <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_number" title=3D"Irrational nu=
mber">irrational numbers</a>. For instance,
</p>
<ul><li>0.10100100010000100000100... does have a pattern, but it is not a f=
ixed-length recurring pattern, so the number is irrational</li>
<li>1.0110101000001001111001100110011111110... is the binary representation=
 of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D=
"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><mat=
